			<div class="bps-topic-search-results">
				
					<div class="bps-topic-search-results-title">
						<h2>More from Britannica on "<span class="bps-open-search-term">Samuel de Champlain (French explorer)</span>"...</h2>
					</div>
					
					
						<div class="bps-open-search-results">
							<h3>Student Britannica Articles (Ages 11 and up) on "<span class="bps-open-search-term">Samuel de Champlain (French explorer)</span>" from the <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/">Britannica Online Student Edition</a></h3>
							<div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/comptons/article-9273593">Champlain, Samuel de</a>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">(1567&ndash;1635). Called the Father of New France, Samuel de Champlain founded Quebec, the first permanent French settlement in North America. He also kept the struggling community alive during its early years. He explored New France (now part of Canada) as far west as Lake Huron and also discovered the lake in New York that bears his name.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/comptons/article-198156">Canada</a>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">Throughout the rest of the 16th century the European fishing fleets continued to make almost annual visits to the eastern shores of Canada. Chiefly as a sideline of the fishing industry, there continued an unorganized traffic in furs. At home in Europe new methods of processing furs were developed and beaver hats in particular grew very fashionable. Thus new encouragement was given to the infant fur trade in Canada. In 1598 Troilus de Mesgouez, marquis de la Roche, set out for Canada armed with a new kind of authority&mdash;a royal monopoly that gave him the exclusive right to trade in furs.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/comptons/article-200489">exploration</a>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">In 1576 Sir Martin Frobisher, seeking the Northwest Passage, traveled the Canadian Arctic. Henry Hudson failed to find the Northeast or Northwest Passage but added to the knowledge of the Arctic and North America. He discovered Hudson Bay in 1610. Samuel de Champlain, in the early 1600s, was the first to systematically investigate the New England coast. (See also Hudson, Henry; Champlain.)</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/comptons/article-207032">Quebec</a>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">The massive gray rock of Cape Diamond stands above the entrance to the upper river. It was recognized as a defense point by the Indians long before the arrival of the first white settlers. In 1535 the French explorer Jacques Cartier found here the large Indian village of Stadacona. In 1608 Samuel de Champlain founded a settlement below the heights and called it Quebec. The name comes from an Algonquian Indian word meaning &ldquo;where the river narrows.&rdquo;</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/comptons/article-204607">Michigan</a>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">In about 1618 &Eacute;tienne Brul&eacute; became the first European to discover the area that is now Michigan. He had been sent by Samuel de Champlain to find the Northwest Passage (see Champlain). In 1634 Jean Nicolet, also sent by Champlain, passed through the Straits of Mackinac and explored the southern shore of the Upper Peninsula. In 1668 Father Jacques Marquette organized the first permanent white settlement within the present state at Sault Ste. Marie. Three years later he established a Jesuit mission at St. Ignace. (See also Marquette.)</div>
</div>
							<div class="bps-open-search-result">
								<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/search?ct=ebi&amp;query=Samuel de Champlain">
									More Student Britannica results...
								</a>
							</div>
						</div>
					
					
						<div class="bps-open-search-results">
							<h3>Children's Encyclopedia Articles (Ages 8-11) on "<span class="bps-open-search-term">Samuel de Champlain (French explorer)</span>" from the <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/">Britannica Online Student Edition</a></h3>
							<div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/ebk/article-9352938">Samuel de Champlain</a><span class="bps-open-search-from-article">(from the Champlain, Samuel de article)</span>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">(1567&ndash;1635). The French explorer Samuel de Champlain traveled along North American seacoasts, lakes, and rivers early in the 1600s. Known as the Father of New France, he founded the city of Quebec and promoted French settlement in what is now Canada. He was the first European to sight the lake in New York that now bears his name.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/ebk/article-219722">Early Life</a><span class="bps-open-search-from-article">(from the Champlain, Samuel de article)</span>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">Samuel de Champlain was born in 1567 in Brouage, a small port on the west coast of France. His father was a sea captain. Young Samuel learned seamanship, navigation, and mapmaking. He served in the army and took part in sea voyages to the West Indies.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/ebk/article-218932">History</a><span class="bps-open-search-from-article">(from the Vermont article)</span>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">The Abnaki Indians who originally lived in the Vermont region survived by hunting and fishing. The first European to visit the area was the French explorer Samuel de Champlain in 1609. He discovered a lake there to which he gave his name. No permanent settlement was made until the French built a fort on Isle La Motte in Lake Champlain in 1666. Both the Dutch and the British established settlements in the area in the 18th century.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/ebk/article-219040">Exploration and Settlement</a><span class="bps-open-search-from-article">(from the Ontario, Lake article)</span>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">In 1615, the French explorers &Eacute;tienne Br&ucirc;l&eacute; and Samuel de Champlain visited Lake Ontario. During the late 1600s and early 1700s the French began to build forts in the region. They fought with the British for control of the area many years. The British finally gained control in 1763 as a result of the French and Indian War. Settlement, trade, and shipping in the region then developed rapidly.</div>
</div><div class="bps-open-search-result">
<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/ebk/article-220200">History</a><span class="bps-open-search-from-article">(from the Huron, Lake article)</span>
<div class="bps-open-search-description">Lake Huron was the first of the Great Lakes to be explored by Europeans. Samuel de Champlain, a French explorer, was the first European to see the Great Lakes. He reached the shores of Lake Huron in 1615. In 1669, French-Canadian explorer Louis Jolliet canoed down the lake. Ten years later, the French explorer known as Sieur de La Salle also crossed the lake.</div>
</div>
							<div class="bps-open-search-result">
								<a class="bps-open-search-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://student.britannica.com/search?ct=ebkids&amp;query=Samuel de Champlain">
									More Children's Encyclopedia results...
								</a>
							</div>
						</div>
					
				
				<div class="bps-topic-mw-link">
					For a definition of "<span class="bps-open-search-term">Samuel de Champlain (French explorer)</span>", visit &nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090414232618/http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Samuel de Champlain">Merriam-Webster</a>.
				</div>
